/*--------------------------------*- Choupo -*-----------------------*\
  Henry's-law constant for methylcyclohexane in liquid water (infinite dilution).

  Source DATA: Sander, R. (2015) "Compilation of Henry's law constants
  (version 4.0) for water as solvent," Atmos. Chem. Phys. 15, 4399-4981.
  doi:10.5194/acp-15-4399-2015.   Licensed CC-BY 3.0.
  Redistributed via the open-source `thermo` library (C. Bell, MIT code);
  the Sander DATA retains its own CC-BY licence (honoured here).

  CHANGES (indicated per CC-BY): Sander's van't Hoff form for the
  pressure / mole-fraction Henry constant,  ln H_xp[Pa] = A + B/T,
  was converted to Choupo's parameterisation
        H_ref     = exp(A + B/T_ref)      [Pa] at T_ref = 298.15 K
        enthalpy  = R * B                 [J/mol]  (dH_diss)
  with A = 41.1642, B = -6466.08  (CAS 108-87-2).

  NOTE: INFINITE-DILUTION coefficient -- physically appropriate for
  sparingly-soluble solutes.  For water-miscible species (alcohols,
  ketones, amines, acids) it is only the dilute limit; prefer an
  activity-coefficient model for the full composition range.

  Validity: ~273-373 K near 1 atm (linear Henry form).  For strong
  electrolytes / high loading switch to a Pitzer / eNRTL model.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

solute      methylcyclohexane;
solvent     water;

model       vantHoff;
H_ref       2.8752e+08 Pa;
T_ref       298.15 K;
enthalpy    -53759  J/mol;
Trange      ( 273  373 );
